class Solution {
public:
    bool canMakeSubsequence(string str1, string str2) {
        int n = str1.size(), m = str2.size();
        if (m > n) return false;
        int j = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < n && j < m; ++i) {
            char c = str1[i];
            char next = (c == 'z') ? 'a' : c + 1;
            if (c == str2[j] || next == str2[j]) {
                ++j;
            }
        }
        return j == m;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Greedy two-pointer scan: for each character in str1 we check if it matches the current character in str2 either unchanged or after one cyclic increment. If so we advance both pointers; otherwise only the str1 pointer. If we exhaust str2 we succeed. This single pass is optimal and uses constant extra space.

